    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>7<hi rend="superscript">th</hi></date>
                    <salute>My dear H.</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>Perhaps Riley may have sent you the larvæ of the Pronuba moth so as to fertilise the Yuccas. As I have no plants, I forward them by this post to you, with his brief instructions.— It is the most wonderful case of fertilisation ever published.—<ref target="#foot.f2"/> Do try them, or give them away or throw them away.</p>
<p>Yours affec<hi rend="superscript">t</hi>. | C. Darwin</p>
<p>We have asked D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Klein, Günther &amp; L<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>. Monteagle here for next Sunday,— Carriage at Orpington for 4<hi rend="superscript">o</hi>12<hi rend="superscript">’</hi> Train on Saturday. <hi rend="doubleUnderline">Any hope of you</hi>?<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p> 
                </div>
            </div>

        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The month and year are established by the reference to a visit by <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_2716.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Edward Emanuel Klein</ref> to Down House, and by the reference to <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_6653.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Riley 1873</ref> (see nn. 2 and 3, below).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_4008.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Charles Valentine Riley</ref> described the pollination of <hi rend="italic">Yucca</hi>, which occurs during oviposition of the yucca moth <hi rend="italic">Pronuba yuccasella</hi> (now <hi rend="italic">Tegeticula yuccasella</hi>), in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_6653.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Riley 1873</ref>. An offprint of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_6653.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Riley 1873</ref> is in the Darwin Pamphlet Collection–CUL, and is annotated by CD: ‘Wonderful case of fertilisation, when the moth puts pollen on intentionally’. For more on the pollination mutualism of the yucca and yucca moth, see Pellmyr <hi rend="italic">et al.</hi> 1996.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">CD refers to <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_2716.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Edward Emanuel Klein</ref>, <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1779.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Albert Günther</ref>, and Thomas Rice. <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1218.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Emma Darwin’s</ref> diary (DAR 242) records only Klein’s visit on Saturday 11 and Sunday 12 April 1874.</note>
        </div>        
            
